### API Layer

Keep controllers thin:

```text
api/v1/
```

Example:

```motoko
public shared(msg) func joinRound() : async Result.Result<Text, Text> {
    await LotteryController.joinRound(msg.caller)
}
```

### Service Layer

All business logic:

```text
LotteryService
 в”њв”Ђ Verify entry
 в”њв”Ђ Verify payment
 в”њв”Ђ Verify round open
 в”њв”Ђ Register participant
 в””в”Ђ Return result
```

Controllers should never contain business logic.

### Repository Layer

Only data access:

```text
RoundRepository
EntryRepository
WinnerRepository
```

Never access storage directly from services.

### Storage Layer

All stable memory:

```text
StableRoundStore
StableEntryStore
StableWinnerStore
```

If ICP upgrades the canister:

```text
upgrade
в†“
stable memory survives
в†“
all rounds remain
```

### Versioning

Start immediately with:

```text
api/v1/
```

Later:

```text
api/v2/
```

without breaking old clients.

### Main Canister

`main.mo` should only wire everything together:

```motoko
public shared(msg) func joinRound() : async Result {
    await LotteryController.joinRound(msg.caller)
}

public query func getCurrentRound() : async Round {
    await RoundController.getCurrentRound()
}
```

No business logic in `main.mo`.

### Rules

```text
вњ“ Controllers = request handling
вњ“ Services = business logic
вњ“ Repositories = data access
вњ“ Storage = stable memory only
вњ“ DTOs = API contracts
вњ“ Models = domain entities
вњ“ Validators = all validation
вњ“ Utils = reusable helpers
вњ“ API versioned from day 1
вњ“ No circular imports
вњ“ One responsibility per file
вњ“ Keep main.mo under ~200 lines
```

This structure scales cleanly from a few hundred users to a large ICP application without turning into a monolithic canister codebase.
